{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Microfossils (fossils small enough to require study with a microscope) are typically abundant, easily recovered, and information rich.",
    "Their study has traditionally depended on manual techniques: experts have historically delineated these fossils through time-intensive visual inspection to identify key features, and quantified them through precise measurements (Garcia and Miller 1998).",
    "Such approaches form the basis of the field, but these methods have limitations (Kowalewski 2002).",
    "Manual image analysis is thorough but labor-intensive and prone to human biases, and it faces challenges in scaling to analyze large microfossil datasets efficiently.",
    "To mitigate the drawbacks of manual analysis, semi-automatic approaches that blend human expertise with computer-aided tools have been developed to standardize microfossil image analysis, reducing human error and bias (Rani et al. 2022)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Their study has traditionally depended on manual techniques: experts have historically delineated these fossils through time-intensive visual inspection to identify key features, and quantified them through precise measurements (Garcia and Miller 1998).",
    "Such approaches form the basis of the field, but these methods have limitations (Kowalewski 2002).",
    "To mitigate the drawbacks of manual analysis, semi-automatic approaches that blend human expertise with computer-aided tools have been developed to standardize microfossil image analysis, reducing human error and bias (Rani et al. 2022)."
  ]
}